WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.700
So let's go make it work with order.jsx now.

00:05.700 --> 00:13.420
So we are going to import use context, another very fun hook from React, and we're going

00:13.420 --> 00:21.320
to import cart context from contexts.

00:21.320 --> 00:26.920
We're going to drop, actually we can just replace this part right here.

00:26.920 --> 00:31.120
So cart equals set cart, right, this part, and the only difference thing is we're going

00:31.120 --> 00:38.040
to say is we're going to say use context, cart context.

00:38.040 --> 00:42.560
And now whatever is in this cart context, whatever it can find above it, that is going

00:42.560 --> 00:46.200
to be passed in here.

00:46.200 --> 00:48.040
It's kind of a pleasant API, isn't it?

00:48.040 --> 00:53.520
You just kind of pass it in, and now that's available here.

00:53.520 --> 00:54.520
Here's the fun part.

00:54.520 --> 00:56.600
We don't have to change anything else.

00:56.600 --> 01:04.480
Everything else just works the same way, which is kind of neat.

01:04.480 --> 01:12.300
And now let's go use it in header as well.

01:12.300 --> 01:24.320
So at the top of header, we're going to say import use context from React, and we're going

01:24.320 --> 01:29.120
to import our cart context again.

01:29.120 --> 01:36.120
Man, I put too many tongue twisters in today's workshop.

01:36.120 --> 01:38.000
Cart context is just going to kill me.

01:38.000 --> 01:41.360
At least there's no pizza of the day.

01:41.360 --> 01:43.360
All right.

01:43.360 --> 01:46.880
Here I only need cart, right, and actually I'm not setting the cart anywhere, so I'm

01:46.880 --> 01:54.400
just going to say const cart equals use context.

01:54.400 --> 01:55.400
Cart context.

01:55.400 --> 01:59.120
Again, I'm not using the setter anywhere, so I'm not going to pull it out.

01:59.120 --> 02:07.080
And instead of having five here, I'm just going to have cart.length, right, except what's

02:07.080 --> 02:08.080
wrong with this?

02:08.080 --> 02:09.680
That's a string literal.

02:09.680 --> 02:10.680
Literally a string literal.

02:10.680 --> 02:13.680
There we go.

02:13.680 --> 02:16.480
Cool.

02:16.480 --> 02:28.680
So ideally, if I say add to cart, big double, notice the number up here is correct, right?

02:28.680 --> 02:34.080
Please don't add 100 things in here because the number overflows.

02:34.080 --> 02:36.040
Even two numbers is a bit sketch.

02:36.040 --> 02:41.280
Again, the context API has gotten a lot better than it used to be, but what's hard about,

02:42.280 --> 02:46.720
this use context, cart context.

02:46.720 --> 02:48.240
Let's say that this number starts going up.

02:48.240 --> 02:51.400
In fact, this is actually kind of the classic problem with hooks in general.

02:51.400 --> 02:57.000
I don't know, I'm not a Facebook user, but Facebook used to have this problem where there

02:57.000 --> 03:00.320
would be phantom notifications, right, and then you would click on it and there would

03:00.320 --> 03:02.880
be no notification there.

03:02.880 --> 03:04.520
This was a React problem.

03:05.000 --> 03:12.880
have these inability to track these contexts correctly, and it was a byproduct of that.

03:12.880 --> 03:16.720
It was really annoying and a lot of people got super annoyed by it.

03:16.720 --> 03:21.320
They've much improved this, but the problem is it's all the indirection of where does

03:21.320 --> 03:25.520
this context come from and what is modifying it?

03:25.520 --> 03:29.320
Just by looking at header, let's say I have a bug with header and this number is always

03:29.320 --> 03:33.980
wrong, what modified the context?

03:33.980 --> 03:41.420
It's not immediately apparent from header, because let's say, okay, I know it's cart

03:41.420 --> 03:47.220
context, I'm going to search my code base for cart context and I'm going to go look

03:47.220 --> 03:53.380
in app and I'm going to see where this is created, but this isn't modifying it.

03:53.380 --> 03:55.380
Where is it being modified?

03:55.380 --> 04:02.380
Again, by looking at this, if this was totally unfamiliar code to you, you can't see it.

04:02.380 --> 04:06.500
You have to go through the entire code base to figure out what is modifying this.

04:06.500 --> 04:11.860
You have to eventually land on order.

04:11.860 --> 04:15.180
Now with the imports, it makes it a little bit easier to be able to grep through it,

04:15.180 --> 04:18.380
to be able to find it, but that used to not be true.

04:18.380 --> 04:24.500
It used to be really opaque of where it's coming from, but it's strange in the structuring

04:24.500 --> 04:30.060
of this app that doing something over here affects something over here.

04:30.060 --> 04:33.900
They provide for it because that's just how websites work, right?

04:33.900 --> 04:38.220
But in terms of beautiful, clean code, it sucks.

